We further analyzed the surface chemical state on the surfaces of as-prepared samples by X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS). The XPS spectra (Fig. 7
                        ) clearly show the presence of Fe, O, C and N peaks α-FeOOH/α-Fe2O3@CHS and α(β)-FeOOH/α-Fe2O3@CBS. Fig. 7A reveals the Fe2p XPS spectrum of α-FeOOH/α-Fe2O3@CHS, showing four characteristic peaks. The two strong at 711.73 eV and 725.29 eV are corresponding to Fe 2p3/2 and Fe 2p1/2 spin–orbits in Fe2O3, respectively. In addition, the two broad peaks center at 719.5 eV and 730.9 eV assigned to the shake-up satellites, resulted from the charge transfer screening of Fe 2p electrons [71]. This indicates the presence of Fe3+ ion oxidation state which is also in good agreement with the reported literature [72]. The binding energy of Fe 2p in α-FeOOH/α-Fe2O3@CHS detected a positive shift compared to α(β)-FeOOH/α-Fe2O3@CBS and control β-FeOOH/α-Fe2O3 modified electrode shown in Table S3, indicating that strong electron interaction between α-FeOOH/α-Fe2O3 and S unit in CNDs [73]. Thus, the α-FeOOH/α-Fe2O3@CHS has fast electron transfer which is ideal for dopamine (DA) absorption [74]. Moreover, Fig. 7(C - D) shows the O1s spectra for two bands at 529 eV and 532 eV which are assigned for lattice oxygen FeO and absorbed oxygen FeOOH, respectively. This suggests that the Fe is in two phases Fe2O3 (oxide) and FeOOH (hydroxide), respectively which was confirmed with TGA, XRD, and FTIR analysis. Remarkably, the intensity ratio of FeOOH to Fe2O3 of O1s in α-FeOOH/α-Fe2O3@CHS is 7.23 which is, 1.6× and 2.75× higher than that of α(β)-FeOOH/α-Fe2O3@CBS and β-FeOOH/α-Fe2O3, respectively. This indicates that S-rich CNDs enhance the chemisorbed oxygen on the surface of α-FeOOH/α-Fe2O3@CHS nanocomposite, which is ideal for electrochemical detection [75]. Regarding C 1 s spectra α-FeOOH/α-Fe2O3@CHS can be deconvoluted into three peaks. The main C 1 s peaks 285.5 E eV, 286.9 eV, and 290,4 eV, attributed to C-C/C=C, CO, and CO bonds, respectively shown in Fig. 8
                        (A - B) which reveal the presence of carbon in the nanocomposite.
